#SOC Role in Blue Team

##Overview
This room covers where a SOC L1 analyst actually sits within a company's wider security structure - the reporting hierarchy
above SOC. the department that sits alongside it (Red Team GRC), the specialised defensive roles that exist beyond L1/L2 and
the practical difference between working an internal SOC vs an MSSP. It closes with a scenario challenge matching security
roles to live incidents based on expertise.

## Security Hierarchy

Cyber security decisions in a larger organisation flow from executives (CEO/CFO) down through a CISO. who owns the security 
programme as a whole, down to team leads (SOC Manager, Red Team Lead) managing individual departments, down to the technical 
staff actually doing the work - SOC Analysts, SOC Engineers, GRC Specialists and Penetration Testers. The useful part of this
isn't the hierarchy itself, it's that Blue Team , Red Team, and GRC (compliance/policy) are three genuinely seperate 
departments under the same CISO, not one undifferentiated security team. SOC L1 sits specifically inside Blue Team, alongside
L2 analysts, SOC engineers and a SOC manager.

## Internal SOC vs MSSP

An Internal SOC and an MSSP are functionally different jobs despite the same job title. An internal SOC e.g a bank's own 
security team) protects one organisation's systems, tends to run on a calmer pace and works deeply with a small well known set
of tools and environments, as a result of this they'd see far more incidents in a given year as a result. Both sides of that 
comparison mattered equally to me - the pace difference affects day to day work life balance but the tool breadth difference
affects what skills you actually build faster. An MSSP role would likely accelerate my technical exposure faster early on
at the cost of a high pressure daily pace

## Final Challenge - Matching Roles to Incidents

The final task required assigning the correct specialist to seven live incident scenarios (e.g a SIEM alert on a firewall brute
force, a phishing malware case, a PCS DSS audit requirement, a named threat group actively targeting the company). I matched
each incident by experise rather than seniority or urgency -  for example, routing the PCI DSS audit requirement to the GRC 
Auditor rather than a more senior technical role and routing the FIN7 threat group question to the Threat researcher rather than
SOC L1/L2 analysts since threat group tactics fall under threat intelligence, not general triage. This reinforced the same 
lesson from the Junior Secure Analyst room: correct routing depends on who has the relevant domain expertise for that specific 
problem not just whos most experienced overall

## What this Changed About My Career Thinking

Before this room I thought about SOC L1 mostly as an isolated starting job. Seeing it mapped into the wider structure sitting
under a CISO, alongsie Red Team and GRC as seperate but connected departments made the specialisation taasts beyond L1 feel
like a visible ladder rather than an abstract 'you can specialise later' statement. Its changed how I'm thinking about skills
to build deliberately over the next year rather than just finishing the SOC L1 pathway stopping

